    <main>
      <!-- Intro -->
      <section id="intro" class="hero" aria-labelledby="intro-title">
        <h2 id="intro-title">Hello!</h2>
        <p>
          I’ve always been fascinated by how people and governments make decisions and why even the best evidence can struggle to change them.
          My research bridges behavioral science, economics, and public policy to explore how systems can adapt to the people they serve.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Research Focus -->
      <section id="research-focus" aria-labelledby="research-focus-title">
        <h2 id="research-focus-title">Research Focus</h2>
        <p>
          I study how evidence, behavior, and institutions interact to shape public policy, why good evidence doesn’t always lead to good outcomes, and how policymaking can become more representative, adaptive, and inclusive.
        </p>
        <p>
          My work examines both the policies themselves and the processes that create them: how decisions are made, whose perspectives are included, and what barriers prevent change. I’m especially interested in how policies evolve over time and across generations, influencing opportunity and well-being for people, families, and communities.
        </p>
        <p>I often work across four interconnected systems:</p>
        <div class="focus-wrap" aria-hidden="false">
          <ul class="focus-list" aria-label="Focus areas">
            <li><strong>Opportunity Systems</strong> Education, labor, and social policies that shape access and mobility.</li>
            <li><strong>Place-Based Systems</strong> Urban policy, infrastructure, and local governance that define how communities grow and adapt.</li>
            <li><strong>Environmental and Technological Transitions</strong> Energy, climate adaptation, and the governance of emerging technologies.</li>
            <li><strong>Temporal and Generational Systems</strong> How decisions unfold over time and across generations, affecting families and future opportunity.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <p>
          Across these areas, I study how governments use or overlook evidence, reduce administrative burden, translate research into practice, and build institutions that learn and adapt over time.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Selected Work -->
      <section id="projects" aria-labelledby="projects-title">
        <h2 id="projects-title">Selected Work</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Reimagining the Evidence in Evidence-Based Policymaking</strong>: Graduate research paper examining the economic, structural, and behavioral barriers to evidence use in government, and proposing system-level reforms to make policymaking more adaptive and inclusive.</li>
          <li><strong>Evidence Use in Local Government</strong>: Mixed-methods study of institutional barriers and incentives shaping how cities and states use research in policy reform, with attention to the types of evidence valued across agencies.</li>
          <li><strong>Patterns of Internal Displacement in Afghanistan</strong>: Evaluation of UNHCR survey representativeness against geospatial and cellphone mobility data to understand population movement and data quality under crisis conditions.</li>
          <li><strong>Behavioral Research Operations</strong>: Development of standardized procedures for in-lab and online behavioral studies, improving administrative data documentation, reproducibility, and financial and capacity reporting.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
